The Fragility of the Flat World
The World is Flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman said this. Friedman chose this highly provocative book title for his bestseller to make people aware of the astonishing impact of technology on the world economy.
The distance is shortening.
Geographic barriers can no longer easily provide protection.
Manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals in Europe and the United States all have to face the challenge of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they speak to are likely far away in India.
Skeptics pointed out the limitations of Friedman's analogy.
As someone said, the world is not flat, but "uneven."
The contour map of global economic activity shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of deprivation.
Not only that, but distance is far from losing its significance.
Even neighboring countries with relatively low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, engage in much more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, but Vancouver's trade with the fartheraway Toronto is much greater than its trade with the nearby Seattle.
Although there are such criticisms, Friedman still put forward an important point.
Globalization can be defined as mutual dependence between different continents; its history is as old as human history, witnessing the migration of races and religions, as well as the trade along the ancient Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different; it is developing faster and more deeply.
After the first transatlantic telegraph cable was laid in 1868, Europe and the United States could communicate within a minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes described how a British person living in London could order goods from around the world by telephone and then sit at home waiting for them to arrive in the afternoon.
But Keynes's British person was an exceptional case of the affluent.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can purchase goods from all over the world at their local supermarkets.
In a similar way, real-time global communication emerged twenty years ago, but it was beyond the financial reach of the majority of people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an Internet café and gain access to capabilities that were once only available to the government, multinational corporations, and a small number of individuals or institutions with large budgets.
The significant decline in the costs of computation, communication, and transportation has made technology increasingly widespread.
Just ten years ago, two-thirds of internet users were still concentrated in the United States.
While today, the proportion of Internet users in the United States accounts for less than a quarter of the global total.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who have access to information has reached an all-time high in human history.
Non-state actors now possess capabilities that were once exclusively controlled by the government.
The position of the nation-state as a subject in world politics will not change for the time being, but it must learn to share this vast stage with a growing number of participants, including institutions like the Oxford Food Relief Committee, celebrities such as Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like Al-Qaeda.
But this flattening process is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred before.
The world economy was highly integrated in 1914, but the interdependence among countries in economic terms declined continuously over the next 30 years.
Until 1970, the global economy had recovered to the level of integration it had once known, and at that time it was still heavily constrained by the Iron Curtain.
World War I served as the catalyst for the reversal, and during the two World Wars and one global Cold War, people witnessed a decline in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization.
This reflects deeper issues such as domestic inequality caused by economic development in the 19th century.
Political institutions failed to adapt to economic development, resulting in abnormal ideologies—fascism and communism reaching their peak—which led to the fragmentation of nations and the world.
After World War II, the welfare state system in the West wove a safety net for those harmed by economic changes, encouraging them to accept the benefits of international economic interdependence.
Some analysts argue that China's role today is very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising forces troubled by domestic inequality, constantly developing toward nationalism and challenging the dominant powers, ultimately leading to world wars that reverse the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, were the economies of Britain and Germany not similarly interdependent before 1914?
But such reasoning is not complete.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had already surpassed Britain's.
However, even if China maintains its current high growth rate, its economy is unlikely to catch up with that of the United States within at least two decades.
The forces of non-state and transnational actors unleashed by the spread of technology may pose a greater threat to the flat world.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in an unannounced attack than the Japanese government's attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941.
I call this phenomenon the privatization of war.
If such forces were to acquire nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo a complete transformation.
At that time, the movement of people and goods across borders would become more difficult.
If these forces were to disrupt the oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which accounts for two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, the global economic depression similar to that of the 1930s could further strengthen the forces of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two major driving forces of globalization.
So far, policies have further reinforced the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken the leading role in promoting policies to eliminate obstacles.
But the events described above may reverse this policy.
Some critics of globalization may be willing to see such an outcome.
But such an outcome, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst situation in two areas—that is, the reversal of the economic globalization trend of spreading technology and power, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization would be further reinforced, such as the spread of war, terrorism, climate change, and infectious diseases.
If that were the case, the flat world would become a desert.
